HAZEL SIVE: All right, let's
look at some of your questions.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:35.600
A bunch of them
are-- you know what,

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:38.630
I'm probably going to use
that screen most of the time.

00:00:38.630 --> 00:00:40.050
Because this one's not fitting.

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:42.920
But let's look on this screen.

00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:48.200
Your questions really focused
around IPS cells and the kind

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:51.770
of magic of IPS cells.

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:54.650
And there were a couple of
major questions that came up.

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:00.599
What's the problem with using
IPS cells therapeutically?

00:01:00.599 --> 00:01:01.640
Well, there are a number.

00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:03.500
One, they're so
new that really we

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:10.190
don't know what kinds of cell
types these IPS cells can make,

00:01:10.190 --> 00:01:13.250
so it's not clear
how to use them.

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:15.470
Another problem actually,
which my colleague,

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:18.560
Professor Jaenisch
works on is the question

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:20.885
of how to actually
grow these cells.

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:25.990
I have a voice
issue this morning.

00:01:25.990 --> 00:01:30.430
So you know, the quieter
you are, the more you'll

00:01:30.430 --> 00:01:34.180
be able to hear my words.

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:38.609
IPS cells, human cells, grow
very slowly in the laboratory.

00:01:38.609 --> 00:01:40.150
And it's very
difficult to grow them.

00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:43.090
So there are some basic
questions in biology,

00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:46.510
as to how to grow these
cells to enough numbers that

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:48.190
would actually be useful.

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:50.260
But here's another one
that's very important.

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:51.910
The transcription
factors that we

00:01:51.910 --> 00:01:55.450
use to convert adult
cells into IPS cells

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.690
included an oncogene
called c-Myc.

00:01:58.690 --> 00:02:02.680
And Myc is the kind of gene
you don't want floating

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:05.890
around your body nice
and active in your cells,

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:07.840
because it will give you cancer.

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:11.410
So the challenge is
how to actually use

00:02:11.410 --> 00:02:13.900
Myc and other
potent transcription

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:18.220
factors to turn adult
cells into stem cells

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:21.640
but not have the stem cells
give the recipient cancer.

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:23.260
And there's some
very clever ways

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:25.510
that people are trying
to get around this.

00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:35.520
It is really impossible
to teach you,

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:36.980
if there are groups
of you talking.

00:02:39.640 --> 00:02:41.030
I just cannot do it.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:45.590
So those of you
talking, please don't.

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:47.370
Thank you.

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:50.940
All right, so what's the
big deal about IPS cells?

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:54.540
Well, the big deal is
they can be your own.

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:57.720
In theory-- and maybe
in practice, a decade,

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:00.390
five years maybe from now--

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:04.170
your own cells, your skin cells
could be removed from you,

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:06.270
could be dealt with
in the laboratory,

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:09.180
turned into your own
stem cells, and put back

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:11.350
into your own body,
and they'd be your own.

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:14.670
So of course, they wouldn't
be rejected by you.

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:16.270
And that is an enormous deal.

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:19.240
They're called autologous cells.

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:20.770
There's an ethical
issue, in that

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:26.380
you don't have to harvest any
embryos to get stem cell lines.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:28.240
And that's a big deal.

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:31.690
And here's a conceptual deal.

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:33.310
When we talked
about development,

00:03:33.310 --> 00:03:36.430
we talked about this
directional pathway,

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:38.650
where uncommitted
cells became committed

00:03:38.650 --> 00:03:40.660
became differentiated.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:45.170
It was really thought that
that was a one-way pathway.

00:03:45.170 --> 00:03:48.840
But what IPS cell
technology has shown--

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:51.780
let's look at this--

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:55.250
all right, we can get the idea
from one of these two screens.

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:57.440
What IPS cell
technology has shown

00:03:57.440 --> 00:03:59.390
is that you can reverse
differentiation.

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:01.940
You can take
differentiated adult cells

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.040
and with the right
regulatory factors,

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:07.340
you can turn them
into stem cells.

00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:10.610
And so conceptually,
that's a big deal.

00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:13.400
Very good, great questions.

